#   ABC-001: network-dependent abc/ tests SEGV in system libcurl on a firewalled host instead of timing out

Outbound HTTPS is firewalled in this sandbox (`https://www.google.com/` and friends are unreachable). The abc inet tests ‚Äî `CURLtest`, `POLtest`, both gated on `WITH_INET` ‚Äî are supposed to degrade gracefully (bounded connect timeout, a clean CURL transfer error, the ctest `TIMEOUT` only as a backstop). Instead they *SEGV inside the system `libcurl`* while the multi handle is being driven, so an unreachable network turns a should-be-skippable test into a crash. The crash is *not* a regression (verified by A/B against a clean `~/beagle` baseline ‚Äî same fault address), but it is a real defect in abc's curl/poll integration and must be investigated and fixed. See [Issues], [CLAUDE], [MEM-010].

##  Issues
A firewalled target crashes the curl event loop instead of returning an error.

 -  `CURLtest` (`abc/test/CURL.c`) fetches `https://www.google.com/`; `POLtest` (`abc/test/POL.c`) fetches cloudflare/facebook/fastly/google/aws. With the host firewalled both crash: `AddressSanitizer: SEGV` in `libcurl.so.4+0x2e0e4` ‚Üê `curl_multi_socket_action` ‚Üê `curl_pol_cb` (`abc/CURL.c:52`) ‚Üê `POLLoop` (`abc/POL.c:210`).
 -  The faulting address varies run-to-run (`0x1c780000111a`, `0x0008‚Ä¶111b`, `0x0040‚Ä¶111b`) and the run is non-deterministic (sometimes a plain non-zero exit, sometimes the ASan SEGV) ‚Äî a *wild-pointer READ*, i.e. heap corruption / use-after-free in the multi-socket teardown when the connect fails, not a clean error path.
 -  Expected: an unreachable/firewalled target surfaces as a CURL transfer error under a bounded `CONNECTTIMEOUT`, the test exits non-zero-but-clean (or is skipped); it must *never* crash. The ctest `TIMEOUT` (15s/20s) is a backstop, not the mechanism.
 -  Build context: Debug + ASan, clang, musl/Alpine, against system `libcurl.so.4` (not ASan-instrumented). Pre-existing; the same crash reproduces on a fresh baseline with none of the in-flight changes.

##  Blockers
The faulting frames are inside non-instrumented system libcurl, so ASan can't name them.

 -  Needs a symbolized/valgrind libcurl, or instrumenting the abc side (the `curl_pol_cb` ‚Üí `curl_multi_socket_action` ‚Üí `CURLTick` completion lifecycle) to catch where a freed/stale `curl_multi`, easy handle, or `poller` slot is dereferenced after a failed connect. Likely overlaps [MEM-010] (abc/CURL.c unchecked allocs + handle/slist leaks) and the re-entrant-poller hazard already fixed in MEM-013 (abc/POL.c) ‚Äî the `// p may become invalid if socket is removed` note at `abc/CURL.c:49` is the smell.

##  Planned
Make a firewalled host time out cleanly; fix the teardown UAF; bound the connect.

 -  Repro-first ([CLAUDE] ¬ß17): a deterministic case pointing `CURLGet` at a guaranteed-unreachable target (a blackhole/firewalled `IP:port`, or a forced tiny `CONNECTTIMEOUT`) that asserts a clean timeout/error ‚Äî non-zero exit, *zero ASan reports* ‚Äî under ASan.
 -  Set explicit `CURLOPT_CONNECTTIMEOUT_MS` / `CURLOPT_TIMEOUT_MS` on the easy handle so a firewalled host fails fast and bounded, independent of the ctest `TIMEOUT`.
 -  Audit the failed-connect / socket-removal branch of `curl_pol_cb`‚Üí`curl_multi_socket_action`‚Üí`CURLTick` for use-after-free of the easy handle / `curl_multi` / `poller` slot; fix so a removed socket can't be re-driven.
 -  Re-run `CURLtest`/`POLtest` in this firewalled sandbox: clean timeout, non-zero exit, no SEGV.
 -  Optional: gate these live-network tests behind a reachability probe / opt-in env so a firewalled CI *skips* rather than fails ‚Äî but the crash must be fixed regardless of gating.

